SubTopics: Determine the meaning of words and phrases as they are used in a text, including figurative, connotative, and technical meanings; analyze the cumulative impact of specific word choices on meaning and tone.
Content: :ibox:The following problem has TWO parts. Answer Part A and then answer Part B.
In paragraph 1, Thoreau writes, “The natural day is very calm, and will hardly reprove his indolence.” Which word from paragraph 1 is a synonym for indolence?

A.Choice: evening

B.Choice: fortune

C.Choice: chuckle

D.Choice: idleness

Content: Which phrase from paragraph 1 gives a clue to the correct meaning of indolence?

A.Choice: “to light some work of mine”

B.Choice: “nothing memorable is accomplished”

C.Choice: “singing like the birds”

D.Choice: “'overhead for the passing day'”

SubTopics: Determine a central idea of a text and analyze its development; provide an objective or critical summary.
Content: What is the central idea of passage 1?

A.Choice: People who appreciate the natural world tend to be lazier than other people.

B.Choice: Enjoying nature is just as demanding as working hard to earn a living.

C.Choice: Life is better when you surround yourself with nature and pay attention to it.

D.Choice: It can be difficult to accomplish anything when you are surrounded by nature's wonders.

SubTopics: Determine a central idea of a text and analyze its development; provide an objective or critical summary.
Content: Which detail from passage 2 BEST supports the idea that being immersed in nature helps the brain recover from what modern life does to us?

A.Choice: “... Strayer knows our brains are prone to mistakes, especially when we're multitasking and dodging distractions.” (paragraph 3)

B.Choice: “Our brains, he says, aren't tireless three-pound machines; they're easily fatigued.” (paragraph 5)

C.Choice: “The early evening sun has saturated the red canyon walls; the group is mellow and hungry in that satisfying, campout way.” (paragraph 6)

D.Choice: “Feeling like a beached sea urchin, I walk carefully to a grassy bank along the San Juan River for ten minutes of restful contemplation.” (paragraph 8)

SubTopics: Determine an author's point of view or purpose and analyze how an author uses rhetoric to advance that point of view or purpose.
Content: In passage 2, what is the author's point of view toward David Strayer's research?

A.Choice: The research findings will alarm people enough to change their habits.

B.Choice: The research findings are more interesting to observe than to participate in.

C.Choice: The research focuses on an important issue that has become part of modern life.

D.Choice: The research is based on a complicated theory that can't be proven.

SubTopics: Determine an author's point of view or purpose and analyze how an author uses rhetoric to advance that point of view or purpose.
Content: :ibox:The following problem has TWO parts. Answer Part A and then answer Part B.
How is Strayer's point of view about the experience of being in nature, as the author presents it in passage 2, different from Thoreau's point of view in passage 1?

A.Choice: Strayer tries to explain the experience scientifically, but Thoreau does not.

B.Choice: Strayer is more certain than Thoreau that the experience has positive effects.

C.Choice: Strayer suggests that nature should be experienced with other people, but Thoreau does not.

D.Choice: Strayer pays more attention to the nature around him than Thoreau does.

Content: Which detail from passage 2 BEST supports the answer to Part A?

A.Choice: “When you head out to the desert, David Strayer is the kind of man you want behind the wheel. He never texts or talks on the phone while driving.” (paragraph 3)

B.Choice: “The early evening sun has saturated the red canyon walls; the group is mellow and hungry in that satisfying, campout way.” (paragraph 6)

C.Choice: “Strayer, in a rumpled T-shirt and with a slight sunburn, is definitely looking relaxed. 'I'm more in tune with nature,' he goes on.” (paragraph 6)

D.Choice: “Strayer's hypothesis is that being in nature allows the prefrontal cortex, the brain's command center, to dial down and rest, like an overused muscle.” (paragraph 7)

SubTopics: Analyze how point of view and/or author purpose shapes the content and style of diverse texts.
Content: :ibox:The following problem has TWO parts. Answer Part A and then answer Part B.
Read the sentences from paragraph 2.

:ibox:One has to imagine our father reading with his finger, down the column of rarely helpful want ads in the Westwater Gazette that had come in our week's gunnysack of mail and provisions, in his customary search for a colossal but underpriced team of workhorses, and that inquisitive finger now stubbing to a stop at one particular heading.
How does this excerpt reflect Paul's point of view?

A.Choice: It illustrates his awareness of his father's tendency to chase unrealistic ideas.

B.Choice: It shows his acceptance of his father's desire to make a better life for the family.

C.Choice: It emphasizes his frustration with his father's preoccupation with the newspaper.

D.Choice: It explains his confusion with his father's interest in a housekeeper instead of horses.

Content: How does this point of view affect the content of the passage?

A.Choice: Paul firmly tells his father why they can't have a housekeeper.

B.Choice: Paul calmly explains to his father the problem with the housekeeper.

C.Choice: Paul reluctantly reminds his father that they don't need a housekeeper.

D.Choice: Paul eagerly questions his father's wisdom in wanting to hire the housekeeper.

SubTopics: Analyze how complex characters, events, and ideas develop and interact over the course of a text to impact meaning.
Content: Why does Damon MOST LIKELY ask if the potential housekeeper will do the milking?

A.Choice: He prefers house chores to barn chores.

B.Choice: He's hoping to avoid one of his current chores.

C.Choice: He's trying to understand the work of a housekeeper.

D.Choice: He doesn't know why his father wants a housekeeper.

SubTopics: Determine the meaning of words and phrases as they are used in a text, including figurative and connotative meanings; analyze the cumulative impact of specific word choices on meaning and tone, such as how language evokes a sense of time and place, and how it communicates an informal or formal tone.
Content: In paragraph 8, what do words like “delineation,” “construed,” and “logical extension” suggest about the narrator?

A.Choice: He feels intellectually superior to the rest of his family.

B.Choice: He enjoys irritating his brothers by using words they don't know.

C.Choice: He wants to impress others with his expansive vocabulary.

D.Choice: He has been influenced by his father's way of speaking.

SubTopics: Analyze how complex characters, events, and ideas develop and interact over the course of a text to impact meaning.
Content: What point does Paul try to make in paragraphs 12–14?

A.Choice: He always has to explain to his father why his father's plans won't work.

B.Choice: The person in the advertisement won't help solve the family's biggest problem.

C.Choice: The family wouldn't need a housekeeper if the brothers would do their chores.

D.Choice: He is already responsible for taking care of the cooking and other housekeeping chores.

SubTopics: Determine a theme or central idea of a text and analyze its development; provide an objective or critical summary.
Content: Which statement provides the BEST summary of the story?

A.Choice: A father with three boys considers how to hire a housekeeper for his family.

B.Choice: A young boy tries to convince his father to hire a housekeeper.

C.Choice: A man recalls a time from his childhood when his father wanted to hire a housekeeper.

D.Choice: A man tells a story about a time when his father read an advertisement for a housekeeper.

SubTopics: Determine a theme or central idea of a text and analyze its development; provide an objective or critical summary.
Content: :ibox:The following problem has TWO parts. Answer Part A and then answer Part B.
What is a theme in the passage?

A.Choice: Extreme eagerness can be contagious.

B.Choice: Humor isn't always universally understood.

C.Choice: Hard work is often its own reward.

D.Choice: Desire can make nonexistent problems suddenly appear.

Content: Which detail helps develop this theme?

A.Choice: “Meal-making was not a joking matter in our household.” (paragraph 4)

B.Choice: “... continued to look pleased as could be ...” (paragraph 4)

C.Choice: “... a lack as unbeknownst to them as our need for a housekeeper had been to us two minutes ago.” (paragraph 10)

D.Choice: “He knew — we all knew — I had him there.” (paragraph 14)

SubTopics: Analyze how an author's ideas or claims are developed and refined by particular sentences, paragraphs, or larger portions of a text.
Content: How do paragraphs 1–3 help develop a central idea of the passage?

A.Choice: They explain what acorns are to help develop the central idea that all oak trees produce acorns.

B.Choice: They explain what a boom year is to help develop the central idea that many animals depend on acorns.

C.Choice: They describe contrasting conditions to help develop the central idea that acorn production varies by year.

D.Choice: They describe the results of heavy acorn production to help develop the central idea that acorns are important.

SubTopics: Analyze how an author's ideas or claims are developed and refined by particular sentences, paragraphs, or larger portions of a text.
Content: Read the sentence from paragraph 6.
:ibox:But annual rainfall and temperature fluctuations are much smaller in magnitude than acorn crop sizes.
How does this sentence help the author develop the ideas in the passage?

A.Choice: It reveals that most natural cycles experience variations each year.

B.Choice: It supports the idea that it is a combination of factors that cause mast years.

C.Choice: It demonstrates the excessive amount of acorns that can be produced by oak trees.

D.Choice: It shows that a common explanation for what causes mast years is not supported by fact.

SubTopics: Determine an author's point of view or purpose and analyze how an author uses rhetoric to advance that point of view or purpose.
Content: :ibox:The following problem has TWO parts. Answer Part A and then answer Part B.
What is the author's purpose in the passage?

A.Choice: to suggest that there is a lack of understanding of mast years, and that further study is needed

B.Choice: to reveal that, although the science behind mast years is unknown, the impact of mast years is significant

C.Choice: to explain that, although mast years occur unpredictably, the way mast years affect the environment is unpredictable

D.Choice: to show that the ecological system is closely connected, and this is demonstrated through the effects of mast years

Content: Select TWO phrases from the passage that help convey the author's purpose.

A.Choice: “Like many trees, oaks have irregular cycles of boom and bust.” (paragraph 4)

B.Choice: “Boom times, called 'mast years,' occur every 2–5 years, with few acorns in between.” (paragraph 4)

C.Choice: “Unfortunately, plants and animals are no better at predicting the future than we are.” (paragraph 5)

D.Choice: “Scientists have proposed a range of explanations — from environmental triggers to chemical signaling to pollen availability — but our understanding is hazy and the fact is that we simply don't know yet.” (paragraph 7)

E.Choice: “Whatever the reasons and mechanisms behind acorn cycles, mast years do have ecological consequences for years to come.” (paragraph 9)

SubTopics: Analyze how an author presents and develops key ideas and events to impact meaning.
Content: :ibox:The following problem has TWO parts. Answer Part A and then answer Part B.
What is one of the author's claims about why cycling between lean years and mast years is important for oak trees?

A.Choice: The cycle provides time for the oak trees to grow rapidly during mast years.

B.Choice: The cycle forces potential predators to find sources of nutrition besides acorns.

C.Choice: The cycle ensures that negative impacts from mast years have time to resolve.

D.Choice: The cycle allows oak trees to control the populations of animals that eat acorns.

Content: Select the detail that is the BEST evidence in support of the author's claim.

A.Choice: “Boom and bust cycles of acorn production do have an evolutionary benefit ...” (paragraph 8)

B.Choice: “... in a mast year, predators (chipmunks, squirrels, turkeys, blue jays, deer, bear, etc.) can't eat all the acorns ...” (paragraph 8)

C.Choice: “Years of lean acorn production keep predator populations low, so there are fewer animals to eat all the seeds in a mast year.” (paragraph 8)

D.Choice: “Unhappily, more deer and mice may mean more ticks and, possibly, more incidences of Lyme disease.” (paragraph 9)

SubTopics: Determine a central idea of a text and analyze its development; provide an objective or critical summary.
Content: Which TWO statements, taken together, provide the BEST summary of the passage?

A.Choice: More oak trees are able to grow after a boom year for acorns.

B.Choice: Acorns are a valuable source of nutrition for many different animals.

C.Choice: Scientists are studying oak trees to understand the reasons for differences in acorn production.

D.Choice: Years when there are many acorns can cause an increase in the population of ticks that carry diseases.

E.Choice: Oak trees have cycles in which they produce many acorns one year and few acorns in the years following.
